    <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed"><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> A centrifuge cannot separate salt from water because salt dissolves to form a chemical solution. Centrifuges work by exploiting specific gravity differences between immiscible phases &mdash; such as sand particles suspended in water or oil droplets floating in water. Since a saltwater solution has no distinct phases with different densities, centrifugal force has no effect on the dissolved salt molecules.</p>
